    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/db5e04fd52826e28b1a3da79cbef44c9?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 1106839,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1098090,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1098090/andrey",
                "reputation": 842,
                "display_name": "andrey"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1324567511,
            "creation_date": 1324563111,
            "body": "<p>Have a look on <a href=\"http://gate.ac.uk/sale/tao/splitch8.html#chap%3ajape\" rel=\"nofollow\">JAPE: Regular Expressions over Annotations<\/a>. A formalism based on CPSL (COMMON PATTERN SPECIFICATION LANGUAGE) in old TIPSTER project.<\/p>\n\n<p>It's not true context-dependent (as Context Grammar should be) but it's possible to do context dependent things with it. This is free and open source. And has a lot of Java examples.<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://sprout.dfki.de/XTDLSampleRule.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">XTDL from SPROUT project<\/a> also worth looking. Not sure is it free or not.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 8605095,
            "question_id": 8604793,
            "last_edit_date": 1324567511
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/DIUmU.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 86926,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 241379,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/241379/kenston-choi",
                "reputation": 2952,
                "display_name": "Kenston Choi"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1324630558,
            "creation_date": 1324630558,
            "body": "<p>I'm not sure if you are looking for regex over semantic graphs and tree structures. If it's the case, you can check <a href=\"http://nlp.stanford.edu/software/tregex.shtml\" rel=\"nofollow\">Tregex and Semgrex<\/a> that matches over Stanford dependency graphs and constituent trees.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 8613964,
            "question_id": 8604793
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/DIUmU.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 86926,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 241379,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/241379/kenston-choi",
                "reputation": 2952,
                "display_name": "Kenston Choi"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1327811698,
            "creation_date": 1327811698,
            "body": "<p>I haven't tried <a href=\"http://code.google.com/p/graph-expression/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Graph-Expression<\/a>, but the site states that it provides a language for \"structure of match -it is possible to build syntax tree based on match\". I think this is comparable to JAPE (as it states in the site: \"fast - it works faster then Jape transducer (gate.ac.uk) closest project to this one\"). And I assume it can handle graphs, something JAPE may not be good at.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 9050974,
            "question_id": 8604793,
            "community_owned_date": 1327811698
        }
    ],
